The paper discusses the impact of the digital age on the relationship between journals' Impact Factors and the actual citations received by their respective papers. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), cybersecurity (cs.CR), and social and information networks (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper's focus on the citation rates of papers suggests that it may also be relevant to the sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL), which often involves analyzing patterns of citation and co-citation in academic literature.
